%I A392377 #31 Mar 30 2026 23:57:09
%S A392377 51,85,119,123,153,187,205,219,221,267,291,323,339,357,365,391,411,
%T A392377 425,445,451,459,485,493,533,565,579,595,629,663,679,685,697,699,723,
%U A392377 731,765,771,779,791,803,843,861,867,873,901,935,939,949,965,969,979,1003,1011
%N A392377 Odd k such that A393131((k^2-1)/2) = EulerPhi(k^2)/A329726((k^2-1)/2) is even. In other words, odd k such that the subgroup of witnesses for Solovay-Strassen primality test of k^2 has even index in (Z/k^2Z)*.
%C A392377 If A393131((m-1)/2) = eulerphi(m)/A329726((m-1)/2) is odd and m is not a prime power, then m is necessarily a square.
%C A392377 Odd k such that the subgroup of a satisfying a^((k^2-1)/2) == 1 (mod k^2) has even index in (Z/k^2Z)*.
%C A392377 Odd numbers k such that v(k^2-1,2) <= v(p-1,2) for some prime factor p of k, where v(a,2) is the 2-adic valuation of a.
%H A392377 Jianing Song, <a href="/A392377/b392377.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A392377 51 is a term since {a in (Z/2601Z)* : a^((2601-1)/2) == 1 (mod 2601)} has index 204 in (Z/2601Z)*, so the index is even. Indeed, we have v(2601-1,2) <= v(17-1,2).
%e A392377 45 is not a term since {a in (Z/2025Z)* : a^((2025-1)/2) == 1 (mod 2025)} has index 135 in (Z/2025Z)*, so the index is odd. Indeed, we have v(2025-1,2) > v(3-1,2) and v(2025-1,2) > v(5-1,2).
%t A392377 q[k_] := k > 1 && OddQ[k] && Module[{v = IntegerExponent[k^2-1, 2]}, AnyTrue[FactorInteger[k][[;;, 1]], IntegerExponent[#-1, 2] >= v &]]; Select[Range[1020], q] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 30 2026 *)
%o A392377 (PARI) isA392377(n) = if(n%2==0||n==1, return(0)); my(f=factor(n)[,1]~, r=#f); for(i=1, r, if(valuation(n^2-1,2)<=valuation(f[i]-1,2), return(1))); return(0)
%Y A392377 Cf. A329726, A393131.
%K A392377 nonn
%O A392377 1,1
%A A392377 _Jianing Song_, Mar 13 2026
